ed Kingdom","York,Yorkshire,England.":"York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Escrick,Yorkshire,England.":"Escrick, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Aunay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Hungarian: habitational name for someone who lived in a settlement on the Danube river (Hungarian <i>Duna</i>). In some cases the name may simply be ornamental.","Ukrainian: cognate of Polish   Dunaj  .","Americanized form of Polish and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Dunaj  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunaj","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Krzysztof.","Polish: topographic name from <i>dunaj</i> ‘distant or unfamiliar river’, also ‘abyss’.","Jewish (from Poland): habitational name from the village called Dunaj in central Poland, or artificial name from <i>Dunaj</i>, the Polish name for the Danube river."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Baron Thomas d' Aunay was born about 1332, in York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Elizabeth Durrant. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mrs. Thomas d' Aunay. He died in 1391, in Escrick, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"about 1332–1391":"umbes 1332–1391","1302–1346":"1302–1346","1332–1391":"1332–1391","1337–Female":"1337–Surnud","1360–1393":"1360–1393","1364–1417":"1364–1417","1282–Female":"1282–Surnud","1337":"1337","Abt 1360":"umbes 1360","1346":"